# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Traversing through the linked list maintaining previous pointer and connecting latest found (appearently) non duplicate node as it's next.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. It first checks if the list is empty (has no elements). If it's empty, there's nothing to do, so it returns an empty list.

2. It creates a special node called 'x' and connects it to the beginning of the list. This helps in handling cases where the first element of the list is a duplicate.

3. It sets up two pointers, 'head' and 'prev,' to traverse the list. 'Head' is used to move through the list, and 'prev' keeps track of the previous node.

4. The code then goes through the list one element at a time using a loop.

5. Inside the loop, it checks if the current element has duplicates by comparing its value with the next element's value. If duplicates are found, it marks them and moves the 'head' pointer past all duplicates.

6. If duplicates were marked, it makes the 'prev' node skip these duplicates by updating its 'next' pointer to point to the first non-duplicate element.

7. If no duplicates were found, it updates 'prev' to the current element.

8. It then moves the 'head' pointer to the next element and repeats the process until it reaches the end of the list.

9. Finally, it returns the modified list, which starts from 'x->next,' excluding the initial 'x' node.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N)
Traversing through entire linked list for once.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1)
Not using any extra space.

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * struct ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode *next;
 *     ListNode() : val(0), next(nullptr) {}
 *     ListNode(int x) : val(x), next(nullptr) {}
 *     ListNode(int x, ListNode *next) : val(x), next(next) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* deleteDuplicates(ListNode* head) {
    // Check if the linked list is empty, if so, return NULL
    if (!head) return NULL;

    // Create a new node 'x' and set its next pointer to the head of the linked list
    ListNode* x = new ListNode(0);
    x->next = head;

    // Create a 'prev' pointer to keep track of the previous node while traversing
    ListNode* prev = x;

    // Loop through the linked list
    while (head) {
        // Initialize a boolean 'dup' to false to track duplicate nodes
        bool dup = false;

        // Check for duplicates by comparing the current node's value with the next node's value
        while (head->next && head->next->val == head->val) {
            head = head->next;
            dup = true;
        }

        // If duplicates were found, update the 'prev' node's next pointer to skip the duplicates
        if (dup) {
            prev->next = head->next;
        } else {
            // If no duplicates were found, simply update 'prev' to the current node
            prev = head;
        }

        // Move to the next node in the linked list
        head = head->next;
    }

    // Return the modified linked list starting from 'x->next'
    return x->next;
}
};
```

